<head ><name  type='ancientAuthor'>Aeschines</name></head>
<p ><ref  target='http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/image?lookup=1997.99.0389'><figure  n='1997.99.0389.jpeg' rend='left'/></ref><date  from='-0397' to='-0322'>c.397-c.322 BCE</date> (source: <bibl ><title >OCD</title><edition >3</edition></bibl>). <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Aeschines</name> was an Athenian orator (see <name  n='oratory' type='ancientGenre'>Oratory</name>) who is most famous for his speeches in opposition to <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name>, beginning with a dispute over the outcome of an embassy to <name  type='person'>Philip</name> of <placeName  key='Macedon'>Macedon</placeName> in <date  when='-0346'>346 BCE</date>. These exchanges provide us with much of what we know about the relationship between <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> and <placeName  key='Macedonia'>Macedonia</placeName> during the <date  from='-0350' to='-0335'>middle of the 4th century</date>; they are particularly valuable because they show us two sides of the issues of the day (cf. <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg018' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 18</bibl>, <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg019' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 19</bibl>, <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0026.tlg02' type='cts-urn'>Aeschin. 2</bibl>, <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0026.tlg003' type='cts-urn'>Aeschin. 3</bibl>). (See also the genre of <name  n='oratory' type='ancientGenre'>Oratory</name>.)</p>
<byline >Christopher Blackwell</byline>
